article.description: Pau Gasol had 23 points, eight rebounds and seven assists to help the Grizzlies beat the Pacers 105-75.
article.headline: Gasol has 23 points, eight rebounds, seven assists
article.linkText: Gasol leads Grizzlies to fourth consecutive win
article.story:
MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- The Indiana Pacers were flat, and the Memphis Grizzlies recognized it. Pau Gasol had 23 points, eight rebounds and seven assists to help the Grizzlies beat Indiana 105-75 on Tuesday night. The result marked another double-digit loss for Indiana at a time it's trying to enhance its playoff position. The Pacers, who lost 103-88 to Boston on Sunday, are just percentage points ahead of Milwaukee for the sixth playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. "It was a disappointing performance, I'll leave it at that," Pacers coach Rick Carlisle said. "... We've got two games now where we've had disappointing stretches. We have to do better than that to keep any legitimate playoffs hopes alive." Six players scored in double figures for the Grizzlies, who won their fourth straight game. Memphis increased its lead to double digits in the second quarter and led 84-60 after three. The 30 points was the largest margin of victory for Memphis this season. "I think we just caught them on a flat night," Grizzlies forward Shane Battier said. "When you play a team like that, you've got to recognize it, and you've got to kick concentration up just a notch and kick your energy level up a notch and win the game early." Jeff Foster and Anthony Johnson each scored 15 points for the Pacers, who had only three points in the first 8 minutes of the fourth quarter. Peja Stojakovic and David Harrison had 13 points and 11 rebounds apiece. Indiana has lost three of its last four games. "They did a great job of moving the ball and our defense was just terrible," Foster said. "They were driving at will on us and getting to the basket. If they weren't finishing, they were hitting the 3-point shooters and getting the ball to the perimeter and breaking us down." Memphis, which snapped a three-game losing streak against the Pacers, was never threatened after building the lead in the first half. The Grizzlies closed the first half with an 8-0 run to take a 50-36 lead at the break. Gasol, who had 10 points in the half, finished the surge with a tip-in with 19 seconds left. Battier and Bobby Jackson finished with 14 points apiece for Memphis, while Eddie Jones, Chucky Atkins and Mike Miller each scored 11. Jones had seven rebounds and Miller and Jackson added five assists each. Gasol also had four blocks. "I don't think they packed it in," Jones said of the Pacers. "I just thought we played great defense. I thought we moved the ball incredibly well and got open shot after open shot." Carlisle said there are a number of factors that went into the Pacers' problems, from rebounding to a defensive effort that provided Memphis with enough good looks to shoot 51 percent and 9-of-20 from outside the arc. "We'd like to get out and run and do some good things on offense," Carlisle said. "But if you can't get the stops, it's going to be hard to do that. We're going to have to be better at both ends, but after the last couple of games on the defensive end, that is going to have to become more of a priority for us." Indiana, hindered by injuries already, had to deal with foul trouble against the Grizzlies. Foster, Harrison and Danny Granger had three fouls at halftime. Memphis extended the lead to 26 points in the third period, after connecting on nine of its first 13 shots in the quarter. Gasol had 13 points in the period, including a 22-footer as the shot clock ran out on one possession.

Game notes
Pacers C Foster had nine rebounds, snapping a string of seven games with at least 10 rebounds. ... Indiana F Jermaine O'Neal sat out his 24th game with a left groin tear. O'Neal indicated recently that he expects to return from the injury soon. Jamaal Tinsley also sat out with a sinus infection. ... Pacers F Scot Pollard, who had missed four of the last five games with a sore back and left foot, started for Indiana. ...Memphis' 37-point lead midway through the fourth period tied the mark for the second-highest lead in franchise history.
